.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:1:# Two-Lane Opus Deep Review (017): Review Report
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:3:Second independent deep review of the deep-agent-improvement TWO-LANE program (phases 008-013), in its post-015-remediation state. Reviewer model: Opus 4.8 (1M). Prior review: cli-codex gpt-5.5 (packet 014, CONDITIONAL, 4 P0 plus a P1 cluster), remediated in packet 015. This pass independently re-verifies that the 015 remediation holds and hunts for issues a different model surfaces.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:15:The 015 remediation HELD. Every 015 fix this review sampled is present in the current code, backed by passing tests, with no regression. The space-form parseArgs fix (F-P0-1), the dispatch read-only default plus DEEP_AGENT_DISPATCH_WRITE opt-in (F-P1-1), run-benchmark fixture-id sanitize (F-P1-9), report-history snapshot and provenance (F-P1-13, F-P1-7), grader score clamp on fresh and cache-hit paths (F-P1-4), packet-local plus candidate-keyed score cache (F-P1-11, F-P1-12), separator-bounded isInside containment (F-P1-2), and the TST-1 byte-identity plan all verify in code, and the three in-scope vitest files pass (29 of 29).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:17:This review confirms the program stays CONDITIONAL because of a small cluster of real defects that 015 either did not reach or only partially closed. The headline is a single new partial-remediation gap that a different model surfaced: the 015 F-P1-9 fixture-id hardening was added to run-benchmark.cjs (the second writer) but never ported to materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs (the FIRST writer in the wired plan), so a hostile fixture id still escapes the outputs directory at materialization time. The remaining active P1s are a fail-open hardening-gate coverage gap on the bundle-gate execSync path, three dead "Mode 4" doc anchors that misroute the orchestrating agent, and a non-executable Lane B promotion path whose docs over-claim "mode-aware promotion."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:19:Scope reviewed (read-only): the curated current two-lane code listed in the review brief, spanning loop-host, reduce-state, the fixture materializer, the promoter, the model-benchmark dispatcher and runner, the 5-dim scorer and its deterministic checks and grader, the agent-improvement scorer, the three in-scope test files, both Lane command docs and the auto YAML, SKILL.md, and the skill-advisor explicit lane.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:25:Every P0 candidate and every P1 candidate was re-read at the cited file:line and adversarially re-tested before final severity. Two candidate P1s were downgraded to P2 under the deep-review false-positive discipline, and they are the most important adjudication outcomes of this pass.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:27:**Downgrade 1: correctness-9-1 (Lane B is model-blind), P1 to P2.** Opus surfaced that the wired Lane B loop scores each fixture's own reference content against that fixture's own criteria, never invoking a model, so the aggregate is a model-independent constant (empirically reproduced: aggregateScore 100, benchmark-pass, all rows 100). On cross-check this is NOT a new class. The 014 gpt-5.5 review already raised it as P0 ("Model benchmark never dispatches a model", correctness-1-2). Packet 015 dispositioned it as DOCUMENT-ACCEPT, refuted as an arbiter-upheld intended deferral traceable to 122/007 (raised there as DR-001-P1-001 "model-benchmark route never invokes the generic dispatcher"). Re-opening an arbiter-upheld by-design deferral as a fresh blocker would violate the adversarial discipline. The behavior runs end-to-end, writes a valid report, and corrupts nothing. The legitimate residual that opus DID add is a traceability gap: the shipped docs still assert Lane B "benchmarks a model" (SKILL.md:14,34,42,273) and "score model variants across fixtures" (auto YAML:6) while the wired and 5dim+llm paths both score the materialized reference, not a model candidate. That residual is recorded as a P2 doc-traceability advisory. correctness-9-2 (the unreachable LANE_MODEL_BENCHMARK resolver branch for dispatch-model.cjs) is the structural footprint of the same accepted deferral and stays P2.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:31:**Why security-2-1 stays P1 while security-6-1 drops.** They look adjacent but differ at the load-bearing word. The bundle-gate path is execSync, which IS "shell execution," so SKILL.md:279 literally promises to cover it and does not, a genuine fail-open against a documented control. The grep path is a file read, outside the literal text of the gate. Same scorer, different severity, by the wording of the guarantee each one is measured against.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:47:| F017-P1-01 (was correctness-1-1) | materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs:91 | The materializer does fs.writeFileSync(path.join(outputsDir, `${fixture.id}.md`), ...) with no id guard, and loop-host plans materialize BEFORE run-benchmark, so the materializer is the first writer. Reproduced: a fixture with id "../escaped-by-materializer" caused the materializer to write escaped-by-materializer.md into the PARENT of outputsDir and exit 0, while run-benchmark.cjs assertSafeFixtureId rejects the same id with infra_failure. The 015 F-P1-9 hardening covers only run-benchmark.cjs (the second writer). The run-benchmark-hardening.vitest.ts traversal test (lines 67-79) calls runBenchmark directly without the materializer, so the first-writer path has zero traversal coverage. | Port assertSafeFixtureId / SAFE_FIXTURE_ID into the materializer and call it before the path.join at line 91, ideally via a shared helper. Add a materializer hostile-id regression test. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:48:| F017-P1-02 (was security-2-1) | bundle-gate.cjs:128-157, score-model-variant.cjs:209 | The DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0 gate is applied ONLY to the type=deterministic execSync branch at score-model-variant.cjs:107-115. On the same 5dim pass, score() unconditionally calls runDetCheck(bundle-gate) at :209, and bundle-gate scoreLayer3 selects acceptance with type smoke-run OR (deterministic AND command) and runs execSync(acceptance.command, {cwd, timeout}) with NO env-gate check. The string DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC is absent from bundle-gate.cjs. bundle-gate is the D2 hard gate (weight 0.30). SKILL.md:279 documents the gate as refusing "criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer," which bundle-gate Layer-3 is, so the documented fail-closed guarantee is false. Dormant by default (shipped fixtures carry no command), but live the moment any profile defines a smoke-run or deterministic+command acceptance under --scorer 5dim. | Route bundle-gate Layer-3 through the same env gate (early-return a skipped layer when DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0), or strip acceptance[].command before the virtual fixture is written when the flag is set. Add a type=smoke-run regression asserting no execution under the flag. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:49:| F017-P1-03 (was traceability-3-1) | start-model-benchmark-loop.md:370,497 plus start-agent-improvement-loop.md:514 | All three cite "Mode 4: Model-Benchmark" as the canonical SKILL.md source of truth, and Step 1 at :370 instructs the orchestrating agent to "Focus on Mode 4." rg "Mode 4" SKILL.md returns zero hits. The real heading is "## 4. LANE B: MODEL-BENCHMARK" (SKILL.md:271). The only Mode-N headings are Mode 1/2/2A/3 UNDER "## 3. LANE A: AGENT-IMPROVEMENT", so the dead "Mode 4" label both dangles and collides with the live Lane A Mode headings. The 009/010 Lane-A/Lane-B reorg renamed the structure and the command docs were not updated. | Replace all three "Mode 4: Model-Benchmark" references with "§4 LANE B: MODEL-BENCHMARK" or a stable anchor. Optionally add a doc-lint that command-doc SKILL.md pointers resolve to a real heading. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:50:| F017-P1-04 (was correctness-5-1 + traceability-7-1) | promote-candidate.cjs:153,168,233, auto YAML:174-176, SKILL.md:278, start-model-benchmark-loop.md:409,411,496 | The auto YAML step_promote_candidate invokes promote-candidate.cjs with candidate, target, score, config, manifest, archive-dir, but the Lane B phase_loop runs only loop-host (materialize + run-benchmark) and reduce-state, so there is no candidate write, no score-candidate step, no manifest. promote-candidate.cjs hard-requires --score (line 153) and rejects unless score.status==="scored" (:168) and score.recommendation==="candidate-better" (:233). The Lane B report.json carries status benchmark-complete with no dimensions and no candidate-better recommendation, so promotion cannot execute. Separately the promoter has zero mode/lane branching (the only "proposal"/"mode" token is the proposal-only error string at :174). It is structurally an agent-only promoter (single canonical manifest target at :130, 4-runtime mirror sync at :256, copy candidate over target at :302). So SKILL.md:278 "apply mode-aware promotion", start-model-benchmark-loop.md:409/411/496 "Promotion ... mode-aware", and "promote-candidate.cjs is mode-aware" are untraceable. Genuine record-level mode-awareness DOES exist in reduce-state.cjs:620, which the docs conflate with non-existent promoter mode-awareness. | Pick one: (a) add a Lane B promotion adapter that maps report.json to a scored-shape --score input or a benchmark-mode branch to promote-candidate.cjs, and reword the docs to say records/reducer are mode-aware while promotion is the shared agent-canonical guarded path, or (b) mark Lane B promotion not-yet-wired and remove the executable-looking YAML step. Drop "mode-aware" from the promoter wording until a mode branch exists. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:56:| F017-P2-01 (was correctness-9-1, downgraded) | loop-host.cjs:153-159, run-benchmark.cjs:274, SKILL.md:14,34,42,273, auto YAML:6 | Wired Lane B scores each fixture's own materialized reference against its own criteria. No model is invoked even on 5dim+llm (the grader reads the materialized reference as outputText at :274). This is an arbiter-upheld DOCUMENT-ACCEPT deferral (122/007 to 014/015 F-P0-2). The residual defect is doc over-claim, in that docs still assert "benchmark a model" / "score model variants across fixtures" while the wired reality is fixture-self-scoring. | Reword the Lane B headline framing to match the deferred reality (fixture-driven scoring, with live model dispatch a documented future wiring step), or wire the dispatch step and remove the deferral. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:57:| F017-P2-02 (was correctness-9-2) | loop-host.cjs:48-51,79-81 | dispatch-model.cjs is in LANE_MODEL_BENCHMARK and resolveScriptPath maps it, but planInvocation never plans it, so the resolver branch is unreachable. Structural footprint of the accepted model-dispatch deferral. | Drop the unused dispatch-model.cjs entry from LANE_MODEL_BENCHMARK, or wire the dispatch step. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:58:| F017-P2-03 (was security-6-1, downgraded) | score-model-variant.cjs:82,95 | grep / grep_absent acceptance build path.join(cwdAbs, a.file) with no containment check, and the DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0 gate (worded "shell execution") does not cover these file reads. Bounded (pass/match-count only, no exfiltration) and under the documented trusted-author boundary. | Add a separator-bounded isInside containment check on path.resolve(cwdAbs, a.file) (reuse cwd-check.cjs:85-87), or broaden the gate / add DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_READ. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:59:| F017-P2-04 (was traceability-3-2) | explicit.ts:123-129 | Comment claims the projection exposes "a single canonical node (deep-agent-improvement)", but projection.ts:122 defines a second live node deep-model-benchmark (alias group at aliases.ts:33). The map code correctly targets deep-model-benchmark with a positive boost, so only the comment's single-node model is stale. No routing impact. | Update the comment to describe the current two-node projection. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:60:| F017-P2-05 (was maintainability-4-1) | loop-host.cjs:99-110, materialize:16, run-benchmark.cjs:27, promote-candidate.cjs:35, score-candidate.cjs:42, dispatch-model.cjs | Space-form --key value works in loop-host / materializer / run-benchmark but degrades to boolean in promote-candidate / score-candidate / dispatch-model (=-form only). No shared parser exists, and the contract lives in inline comments. Latent footgun, no current break since each script is invoked with its supported dialect. | Extract a shared scripts/lib/parse-args.cjs with one documented dialect and have all in-scope scripts require it, or document per-script dialects in a NOTES block. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:61:| F017-P2-06 (was maintainability-4-2) | run-benchmark.cjs:335,360 and score-candidate.cjs:292-299 | Integration score implemented twice. run-benchmark uses named constants and normalizes mirror.status || mirror.syncStatus, while score-candidate hardcodes magic numbers and reads only m.syncStatus. A scanner emitting status but not syncStatus scores differently across lanes. | Extract a shared integration-score helper consuming a normalized shape and resolve the status/syncStatus divergence there. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:63:| F017-P2-08 (was maintainability-4-4) | dispatch-model.cjs:42,50,117,264 | The file (a 121-packet file ported from 120/003) mixes "(014 review)" tags (real lineage) with "(122 review)" tags (carried through from upstream dispatch-minimax.cjs). No 122 packet is in this two-lane program's lineage. Misleading provenance. | Normalize the in-file tags to this packet's lineage, or label ported upstream rationale explicitly as "(ported from 120/003)". |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:64:| F017-P2-09 (was maintainability-4-5) | materialize:32,69 and run-benchmark.cjs:80,387 | fixturePathFor is functionally identical in both files and the profiles-dir default literal is hardcoded in both, so the F-P1-4b "resolves identically in both steps" invariant is a hand-maintained byte-alignment contract. | Extract a shared scripts/lib/profile-resolve.cjs exporting the default dir, fixturePathFor, and resolveProfile, and import it in both. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:65:| F017-P2-10 (was security-6-2) | score-candidate.cjs:194-200,572 | readCachedScore returns the parsed blob verbatim without asserting cached.inputHash === inputHash, so the filename is the only integrity binding. The F-P1-11 packet-local relocation materially reduces the surface, and an attacker who can write the cache file usually already controls the candidate. | After JSON.parse assert cached.inputHash === inputHash and cached.status === "scored", and on mismatch treat as a cache miss and rescore. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:66:| F017-P2-11 (was maintainability-8-1) | dispatch-model.cjs:145,381 and run-benchmark.cjs:409,455,503 | Source comments embed bare finding-id-shaped tags in dimension-iter-N form ("(traceability-3-5)", "(maintainability-8-4)", "traceability-4-2/7-5/7-2") that collide with the active 017 review's own emit namespace. Distinct from F017-P2-08 (packet-number tags). | Adopt a packet-qualified citation form so no source comment reuses the bare dimension-iter-N shape an active deep-review emits. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:67:| F017-P2-12 (was security-10-1) | harness.cjs:57-72 | composeGraderPrompt embeds untrusted swe16OutputText in a fenced block adjacent to the grading instruction, so a benchmarked model could fence-breakout and instruct the grader to return score 1.0. clampScore01 only bounds [0,1], not an in-range inflated score. Only on --grader llm (default noop), D4 weight 0.15, and under the current model-blind wiring the graded text is the trusted fixture reference, so this is forward-looking. | Treat graded output as data-only: harden the system prompt against injection and cross-check D4 against the deterministic hallucination-flag det-check on the llm path. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:68:| F017-P2-13 (was security-10-2 + 10-3) | cache.cjs:30-31 and score-candidate.cjs:356-363 | (a) Grader cache root is a fixed in-repo scorer/cache/ location, not run-scoped, and the cache-hit path only re-clamps and never re-validates against key inputs. This is the un-applied analogue of the score-candidate F-P1-11 relocation. (b) scoreDimSystemFitness interpolates candidate-derived command/skill refs into fs.existsSync without sanitization, a traversal-based existence oracle that also perturbs resource-refs-valid. Both bounded: grader cache only on --grader llm, and the existence probe is read-only on a soft dimension. | (a) Anchor the grader cache under the run/packet outputs dir and verify the derived key inside the cached blob on read. (b) Validate cmd and sk to a basename charset (reject separators and .. segments) before interpolating, mirroring SAFE_FIXTURE_ID. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:74:**Did 015 hold? Yes.** Every 015 remediation this pass sampled is present in the current code and backed by passing tests, with no regression observed. The 3 in-scope vitest files pass 29 of 29. Specifically confirmed live: F-P0-1 space-form parseArgs (loop-host.cjs:99-110), F-P1-1 read-only dispatch default plus DEEP_AGENT_DISPATCH_WRITE opt-in across all five executors (dispatch-model.cjs:187-234), F-P1-9 run-benchmark fixture-id sanitize (assertSafeFixtureId rejects ../evil and a/b, reproduced), F-P1-13 / F-P1-7 report snapshot and success-plus-failure provenance, F-P1-4 grader clamp on fresh and cache-hit paths, F-P1-11 / F-P1-12 packet-local plus candidate-keyed score cache, F-P1-2 separator-bounded isInside, and the TST-1 byte-identity plan.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:76:**Agreements (opus independently re-derived 014 classes that 015 left partially open).** The materializer fixture-id traversal (F017-P1-01) is the same traversal class as 014 "Fixture IDs can escape the benchmark output directory" (014 F-P1-9), which 015 closed in run-benchmark.cjs only. Opus extends it to the first-writer materializer that 015 missed. The bundle-gate exec-gate gap (F017-P1-02) is the same surface as 014 "Criteria shell execution defaults open", where 015 added the gate to one of two exec paths. The dead Mode-4 anchors (F017-P1-03) trace to the 009/010 reorg that postdates 014. The Lane B promotion mismatch (F017-P1-04) echoes 014 "Lane B promotion gate references Lane A artifacts." The advisor comment drift (F017-P2-04) echoes 014 "Advisor disambiguation uses alias-shaped penalty ids", now code-correct but comment-stale.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:78:**Severity delta and the key adjudication.** The largest delta is on the model-dispatch class. 014 rated it P0 ("Model benchmark never dispatches a model"), 015 refuted and accepted it as an arbiter-upheld deferral, and opus initially re-raised it at P1 and then, on cross-check against the 015 disposition register and the 122/007 origin, downgraded it to P2 with only the doc-over-claim residual surviving. This is the central second-model value: opus confirms the deferral is real and traceable rather than a dodge, and isolates the one piece (docs still say "benchmark a model") that the deferral did not clean up.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:80:**New classes opus added that 014 did not name.** (1) The first-writer materializer traversal gap as a distinct surface from the run-benchmark guard, with an empirical parent-dir escape repro. (2) The score-cache read-integrity gap (F017-P2-10): the reader trusts the filename hash and never re-validates the embedded inputHash. (3) The grader prompt-injection surface on the llm path (F017-P2-12). (4) The candidate-ref existence oracle in scoreDimSystemFitness (part of F017-P2-13). (5) The four-dialect parseArgs divergence and the integration-score drift (status vs syncStatus) as maintainability hazards. (6) The bare finding-id-shaped source comments colliding with an active review's emit namespace (F017-P2-11).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/017-two-lane-opus-deep-review/review/review-report.md:88:| Workstream | Findings | Lane |
